Heat a #wide frying pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{drizzle}. When the oil is hot, add the @British Beef Mince{250%g}. Break it up with a #wooden spoon{}, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and cook for ~{7%minutes} or until nicely brown. Get on with the rest of your prep whilst it cooks away.

Cut the @Red Onion{1} in half through the root. Peel and then chop into 1cm cubes or as small as you can. Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Remove the core from the @Red Pepper{1} and slice as thinly as possible.

Once your beef has browned, add your onion, pepper and the @Ras-el-Hanout{1%tbsp} and cook for another ~{5%minutes}. Add your garlic and then cook for ~{1%minute} before pouring in the @Chopped Tomatoes{1%400g can}. Half fill the empty tin(s) with @water{300%ml} and add to the pan. Stir in the @Beef Stock Pot{1} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, reduce the heat to medium-low and leave to simmer for ~{20%minutes}. This is your ragout!

While your ragout cooks, put your #kettle{} on to boil. Add the @Couscous{150%g} to a #bowl{} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @black pepper{}. Mix in a drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle} and then pour in the boiling water. Cover the bowl with #clingfilm{} or a #plate{} and leave for ~{10%minutes}.

Cut the top and bottom off the @Courgette{1} and then cut into 1cm thick angled slices. Roughly chop the @Coriander{1%bunch}.

Heat another #frying pan{} over medium heat (no oil) and toast the @Flaked Almonds{25%g} for ~{3%minutes} or until golden brown, then remove from the pan.

> Watch the almonds like a hawk, they burn very easily!

Once your almonds are out of the pan, increase the heat to high and cook your courgette for ~{5%minutes} on each side (without any oil). Once nicely charred, remove your courgette from the pan and keep to the side.

Check your ragout for seasoning and add more salt and pepper if necessary then stir through your coriander.

Put a spoonful of couscous into your #bowls{} and then pop a couple of courgettes on top. Finish with your spiced beef ragout and a sprinkle of toasted almonds. Enjoy!